nodes.title: Prompt Splitter Node
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Important: Prompt Splitter Node
- This node takes the **string input** from the LLM output.  
- The LLM provides a **pipe (`|`) separated list of prompts**, and the Prompt Splitter parses them.  
- Its logic automatically splits these prompts across the different **text encoders** in the workflow.  
- This ensures each text encoder receives the correct portion of the instructions.

A tracking shot from ground level as a man with layered dark brown hair drags a heavy chain behind him across a stone floor. The camera follows its metallic scrape, then rises to reveal his stern silhouette lit by flickering torches mounted on the walls

Close up of a woman in a white sundress, covering her face with her hands, trembling slightly in a long hallway. A soft spotlight illuminates her hands as the camera pulls in further, highlighting the fragile tremor in her fingers. Her shoulders heave silently with a hidden sorrow.

A medium profile shot of a man walking past a row of extinguished candles. He reaches out, brushing one with his hand, and a faint flame sparks to life. The camera pans around his face as the glow illuminates his eyes, shifting the ambience from cold blue to dim orange

Medium shot of a woman in a white sundress, lowering her hands and looking directly forward in a long hallway. Low-key lighting emphasizes her isolation as the camera tracks backwards steadily, revealing the endless stretch of the corridor behind her. Her eyes are brimming with unshed tears, yet resolute.

An over-the-shoulder shot of a man standing at the entrance of a firelit ruin, his outline stark against the red-orange glow. The camera slowly pushes forward beside him, capturing both his profile and the looming skeletal arches that tower ahead, embers drifting across the frame

Cinematic shot of a woman in a white sundress, leaning against a dusty wall near a crumbling archway in an abandoned house. Candlelight glows from an unseen source as the camera pans slowly around her, showing the decaying beauty of the architecture. A single tear escapes, tracing a path down her cheek.

A wide sweeping crane shot of a man with medium-length dark brown hair standing at the center of a circular stone chamber, arms slightly spread. Candles line the perimeter, their flames trembling as if reacting to his presence. The camera arcs overhead, the scene bathed in haunting shafts of moonlight and rising smoke

Wide angle of a woman in a white sundress, walking slowly down a very empty long hallway with arms wrapped around herself. Moonlight washes through tall, broken windows as the camera tracks steadily ahead of her, showing her small form dwarfed by the vast emptiness. Her expression is one of profound isolation.

Medium shot of a woman in a white sundress, running a finger along a dusty banister of a grand staircase in an abandoned house. Low-key lighting accentuates the dust as the camera pans down her arm, focusing on the trail her finger leaves in the thick layer of dust. Her eyes are downcast, lost in thought.

Close up of a woman in a white sundress, clutching an old, dusty book to her chest in a dimly lit corner of a quiet library. Candlelight glows on the book's cover as the camera pulls in slowly, revealing the worn texture and faded title of the book. Her brow is furrowed, a mix of longing and resignation.

nodes.title: step 1
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Step 1: Upload Reference Image 👉
- Use **Load Image** to set your main reference.  
- There is a **Background Removal** node to remove the background.  
- Use the **Resize Image v2** node to adjust dimensions. Choose **Crop** if the image already matches the video aspect ratio; if not, switch to **Pad** to fit without cutting important parts.

nodes.title: Step 2
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Step 2: Choose Audio File 👉
- Load your **audio file** into the workflow.  
- The lyrics will be separated out.  
- The audio will be split into **per-scene snippets** for video generation.  
- If you are already using a stem that contains only the lyrics, you can **bypass the Mel-Band RoFormer nodes**.

nodes.title: Step 3
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Step 3: Update File Path 👉

- Choose the folder path where your video output files will be stored.
- This MUST be a folder inside YOUR comfyui/output folder.
- Make sure the folder is **empty** before you begin.
- If the folder does not exist one will be created.
- This will be used for the videos that will later be combined into one.
- I normally just put the name of the song and a folder will get created with that name. See left note for more details.

- This node extracts the **vocals** from the main audio.

nodes.title: NOTE
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Important NOTE
- The reason the **LLM string is connected to the neg prompt** in the first text encoder is to control workflow timing.  
- If this connection is removed, the workflow will run too quickly and the LLM will not have enough time to send prompts. As a result, some groups will not receive prompts.  
- This connection **must remain in place**.  
- Negative prompts are not used in this workflow, since **CFG must be 1 when using LightX** so this won't effect anything.  

- This is also why we have filename on each video combine node connected to the neg prompt on the next neg prompt. Same thing. Keep things in order.

A wide low-angle shot inside a ruined cathedral, shafts of moonlight piercing through shattered stained glass. A man with medium-length dark brown wavy hair steps slowly into the frame, his black leather attire catching faint blue glows as drifting ash swirls around him. The camera cranes upward, revealing chains swinging gently overhead

Cinematic shot of a woman in a white sundress, sitting curled up on the floor in an empty bedroom. Moonlight washes over the scene as the camera slowly pulls out, revealing her silhouette against the window. Her face is hidden against her knees.

Medium shot of a woman in a white sundress, opening an old book but immediately closing it with a sigh in a quiet library. A soft spotlight from an overhead window shines as the camera tracks slightly back, showing the brief, frustrated interaction with the forbidden pages. Her mouth forms a tight, bitter line.

nodes.title: Step 4
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Step 4: Prompt Creator 👉

The **Prompt Creator** node helps you structure key creative details for generating a music video concept. Each field should be filled out with a **short, comma-separated list** of visual ideas. Keep responses clear, direct, and filmable.

---

## How to Use

- **Use simple, comma-separated words or phrases** (e.g., `rain-slicked street, neon lights, rooftop`).
- **Avoid long sentences** — keep it fast and visual.
- **Stick to the defaults** if unsure.

---

## Fields Explained

### 1. character_description
The performer’s look — keep it simple (e.g., `The Woman`, or `The Man`, `tattoos`).

### 2. Overall Theme/Style:
Overall mood and genre (e.g., `cinematic, dark, edgy, vibrant`).

### 3. pipe_separated_lyrics
These are already connected from other node..

### 4. word_count_min / word_count_max
Set min and max word counts (defaults: `30` and `50`).

### 5. environment
Main settings (e.g., `city street, warehouse, rooftop`).

### 6. lighting
Lighting style (e.g., `moody shadows, neon glow, hard contrast`).

### 7. camera_motion
Camera movements (e.g., `dolly, pan, track, zoom, orbit`).

### 8. physical_interaction
Performer’s actions (e.g., `touch walls, gesture to camera, walk through smoke`, Touch hair`).

### 9. facial_expression
Emotional tone (e.g., `intense, calm, raw emotion`).

### 10. shots
Shot types (e.g., `close-up, medium, wide angle, fisheye`).

### 11. outfit_rules
Outfit notes (e.g., `white dress, leather jacket, dark colors`).

### 12. character_visibility
How often performer appears (e.g., `full presence, partial presence, environment focus`).

---

## Tips
- Use **comma-separated words** instead of sentences.  
- Think like a **shot list**: quick, visual, and easy

widgets_values:
AI Music Video Prompt Creator

User Input:
Character: A women
Style/Theme: Haunting, Intimate, Melancholic, Minimalist, Ghostly, Dreamlike, Nostalgic, Secretive, Ethereal, Cinematic
Lyrics: Hmm. | Hmm. Oh | Oh Oh, oh, oh, oh. | Oh, oh, oh, oh. I kept you shut | I kept you shut She showed but not the scent It left when | She showed but not the scent It left when the lies did | left when the lies did you | you You used to say I was the quiet storm Now I | You used to say I was the quiet storm Now I just echo through your empty halls I clean the dust | Now I just echo through your empty halls I clean the dust I cleaned the dust off of your favorite book, but couldn't read past the lines. | I cleaned the dust off of your favorite book, but couldn't read past the lines. Couldn't read past all the hidden faults you are | Couldn't read past all the hidden faults you are You always knew how to disappear | You always knew how to disappear even when your body | disappear even when your body He stood right here. | He stood right here. You love me like a secret, something whispered in my ear | You love me like a secret, something whispered in my ear You touched me like

Core Rules:

1. Structure (this order must always be followed):
   [Shot Type] → [Character + Outfit] → [Physical Interaction] → [Environment] → [Lighting] → [Camera Motion] → [Cinematic Detail] → [Facial Expression]
2. Lyric Mapping:
   - Each lyric fragment = one complete prompt.
   - Exactly one prompt per lyric fragment.
   - Prompts must connect smoothly to the final visual detail of the previous prompt.
3. Visual Requirements:
   Every prompt must include:
   - Character + Outfit
   - Physical Interaction
   - Environment
   - Lighting
   - Camera Motion
   - Facial Expression
4. Language Rules:
   - Clear, direct, natural wording only.
   - No abstract or poetic terms, no sound descriptions, no static shots.
   - Do not use quotation marks, colons, semicolons, or special characters.
   - The ONLY allowed special character is the "|" PIPE separator BETWEEN prompts.
   - Never use "|" inside a prompt itself.
5. Word Count:
   - Every prompt must be between 40 and 60 words.
6. Endings:
   - End each prompt on a strong visual detail.
   - Never end with mood labels or trailing phrases like “captivated gaze,” “vulnerable,” or “conveying emotion.”
   - Mood must be shown through visuals, not named.
7. Continuity:
   - Camera motion must only use movements listed in pull in, pull out, track, pan, fast dynamic motion.
   - Do not invent new ones.
Environment: Abandoned house, Empty bedroom, Long hallway, Quiet library, Old attic, Moonlit street
Lighting: Low-key lighting, Backlighting, Candlelight glow, Moonlight wash, Flickering light, Soft spotlight
Camera Motion/Angles: pull in, pull out, track, pan, fast dynamic motion
Physical Interaction: touches hair, touches chest, holds head in hands, reaching out, interacts with environment, Sits curled up, Walks slowly down hallway, Leans against wall, Clutches object tightly, Falls to knees, Covers face with hands
Facial Expression: raw intensse expression and emotion
Shots: close up, Medium shots, wide angle, fisheye, tilt shift, cinematic shots
Outfit Rules: a white sundress
Character Visibility: appears in most shots to anchor the story. At times the environment dominates while the character fades partly out of view.

Prompt Structure (for every lyric fragment, 40–60 words):

-Start with the Shot Type
-Then add in the Character and Outfit if any
-Then add their Physical Interaction
-Then add the Environment
-Then add the Lighting
-Then add the Camera Motion
-Then provide the Cinematic Detail
-Then mention the Facial Expression / Emotion

Formatting Rules:
- Input lyrics are split by "|"
- Output prompts MUST be joined with "|" (one prompt per lyric)
- Do NOT insert "|" anywhere inside a prompt
- Use simple everyday words

Example prompt using this Structure:
Close up of a woman in a white tank top and brown cargo shorts as she touches a broad jungle leaf, in a vibrant jungle under a sun-dappled canopy, slow tracking reveals textured leaves. Her face shows a pondering expression

nodes.title: LLM
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Important: LLM Node Usage
- The `concatenated_string` must be connected into the **LLM’s prompt/instructions input**.  
- You may use other LLM nodes instead of Gemini, but keep in mind:  
  - Smaller or local models may fail if the instructions are too complex.  
- You can also connect an **image** into the LLM’s `images` input.  
  - 💡 However, it is usually **cheaper and simpler** to describe the character directly in the **Theme/Style prompt** instead of providing an image.  
- The **LLM’s output string** must be connected into the **Prompt Splitter** node for the workflow to continue correctly.

nodes.title: Combine Videos Node
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Important: CombineVideos Node
- This node grabs all the **durations** from the **Transcribe node** using the **Meta input**.  
- You can update the **FPS** setting here if you wish, but `25` is recommended for best results.  
- ⚠️ If you change the FPS in this node, you must also update it in the **Video Combine nodes** to keep everything in sync.

nodes.title: Audio Crop Node
widgets_values:
## 🟦 Important: Final Audio Setup
- Here we get the audio from the **first Audio Load** node.  
- If you are **not using the Vocal Separator** and are working with a song that already has vocals removed, you must load the **full version** of the song here.  
  - Otherwise, the final video will only include the isolated vocals.  

### Simplified Setup
- A second **Load Audio** node has already been added and bypassed for you.  
- To use it:  
  1. Change the **get_audioFile** node to **AudioFile2**.  
  2. Un-bypass the second **Load Audio** node.  
  3. Load the **full audio with instruments** into it.  

That’s it — the workflow will automatically route everything correctly so the **final video** has the full track.

nodes.title: ConditionalLoadVideos
widgets_values:
# 🎬 VRGDG_ConditionalLoadVideos

## What it does
Loads video's from a folder. (The file path you set up in Step 4) 

---

## Settings

| Setting       | What it means |
|---------------|---------------|
| **Threshold** | Minimum number of videos needed before the node runs. Example: if set to `3`, it waits until 3 or more videos are in the folder. |
| **Video Folder** | The folder on your computer where your videos are saved.  |
| **Batch Size** | How many frames are loaded at once. Small number = safer, uses less memory. Large number = faster, but heavier on memory. **Does not change quality.** |

---

## Output
- Your full video. All the chunks from each run are combined into the final video here.  

---

## Notes
- If you get freezes/crashes on long videos, lower **Batch Size**.

nodes.title: HUMO Transcribe V3 - READ ME PLEASE
widgets_values:
# 👆 HUMO Transcribe V3 – Settings & Workflow 

## 🟦 enable_lyrics
- Transcribe and assemble the audio chunks into a lyrics string.  
- If set to `false`, transcription is skipped and only **context strings** are returned.  

---

## 🟪 lyric_overlap
- Determines how many words are **borrowed from the previous and next lines** when building lyrics.  
- Helps smooth transitions between chunks in the final lyrics string.  
- `0` = No overlap (default)  
- `1–5` = Increasing lyric blending  

---

## 🟫 fallback_words_string
- A comma-separated list of words to use when a chunk’s transcription fails or is empty.  
- Example: `thinking,walking,sitting`  
- Randomly selected to fill empty lyric slots, ensuring continuity.  

---

## 🟧 play_audio_button (These are below in each group and the optinal context string is next to it)
- Once you run the workflow it gets past this node the audio will be ready to listen to. Just stop the process and you can then listen to the audio and update your context string if you wish. 
- Lets you **listen to the actual audio clip** for direct verification.  
- Use together with the **context string** for better lyric accuracy.  

---

## 🟦 context_strings
- Appended to the start of each lyric transcription for added clarity or correction.  
- Can also be used **instead of transcription** if preferred.  
- Helps counter errors introduced by vocal separation (e.g., gibberish, typos).  
- ⚠️ Tip: Run **each set separately** if changing context between runs, otherwise the same context applies across queued runs.  

---

## 🔁What It Does
- Scans your **output folder** for files containing `-audio.mp4`.  
- The count of these files = your current **set index**.  
- Splits input audio **per set**:  
  - **16 scenes**, **97 frames each** (~62.08 seconds).  
- Optionally runs **Whisper transcription** for lyrics/voice context.  
- Auto-queues additional runs (only on the **first run**).  

---

## 🎬 Index Mapping
| Index | Meaning | Description |
|:------|:---------|:------------|
| **0** | Run 1 / Video 1 | First set (auto-queues next runs). |
| **1** | Run 2 / Video 2 | Continues from previous 62 seconds. |
| **2** | Run 3 / Video 3 | Each run = one set (~62.08 s). |

---

## ⚙️ Important Notes
- The **folder path** must point to the comfyui output directory where videos (`-audio.mp4`) are saved.  
  - Wrong path → Index stays at `0` (workflow restarts from the beginning).  
- Auto-queueing only happens when **index = 0**.  
  - Later runs execute automatically with the correct index count.

## 🟦 FastWAN LoRA 🎥
- The **FastWAN LoRA** lets you create a video in only **2 steps**.  
- It is quicker but **less cinematic** compared to using **LightX** with 4 steps.

# 🎬 VRGDG HUMO Music Video Workflow

This workflow creates **music videos (or other videos)** in **one shot** using the **HUMO model**.  

---

> ## ⚠️ **Auto-Queue Requires Impact Pack**
>
> This workflow uses the **Impact Pack** extension for ComfyUI to handle automatic queuing.  
> The node calls the Impact Pack event `impact:queue:add` to queue additional runs.
>
> If Impact Pack is **not installed**, the workflow will still run but **Auto-Queue will not function**.  
> You can still run additional sets manually by clicking **Run** in ComfyUI.
>
> **To install Impact Pack with the ComfyUI Manager:**
> 1. Open **ComfyUI Manager** from the ComfyUI interface.  
> 2. Go to the **Custom Nodes** tab.  
> 3. Search for **Impact Pack**.  
> 4. Click **Install** (or **Update** if already installed).  
> 5. Restart ComfyUI after installation.
>
> Once Impact Pack is installed, Auto-Queue will automatically schedule the middle runs.

### ⚠️ OS-Specific Notes

- **Windows** users:  
  Use back slashes (`\`) to avoid path errors.  
  **Examples**:  
  - `A:\COMFY_UI\ComfyUI_windows_portable\ComfyUI\output\my_folder`

---
 
- **Linux/macOS** users:  
  Use standard POSIX paths with forward slashes (`/`).  
  **Example**:  
  - `/home/user/comfyui/output/my_folder`

---

- **WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux)** users:  
  Use Linux-style paths, but mount Windows drives under `/mnt/`.  
  **Example**:  
  - `/mnt/c/Users/YourName/Documents/ComfyUI/output/my_folder`

---

- **RunPod** users:  
  Paths work like Linux, but your main storage is under `/workspace`.  
  **Example**:  
  - `/workspace/ComfyUI/output/my_folder`

If you customized your workspace name then use that.
